sentence-detokenized: FOOTBALL - JAPAN GETS A LUCKY WIN, CHINA GETS A SURPRISING DEFEAT.
Japan began the defence of their Asian Cup title with a successful 2-1 win over Syria in a Group C championship match on Friday.
But China saw their luck run out in the group's second match, falling surprisingly 2-0 to newcomers Uzbekistan.

China controlled most of the game and saw several chances missed until the 78th minute when Uzbek striker Igor Shkvyrin took advantage of a misdirected defensive line and lobbed the ball over the onrushing Chinese goalkeeper and into an empty net.
Oleg Shatskiku made sure of the win in added time with an unstoppable left-footed shot from just outside the penalty area.
The former Soviet republic played in an Asian Cup final for the first time.
Despite winning the Asian Games title two years ago, Uzbekistan are underdogs in the final.
Two goals from defensive mistakes in the last six minutes allowed Japan to come from behind and take all three points in their opening encounter against Syria.

Takuya Takagi scored the winner in the 88th minute, when he rose to meet a Hiroshige Yanagimoto cross towards the Syrian goal that goalkeeper Salem Bitar appeared to have covered, but then let slip into the net.
It was Syria's second costly mistake in four minutes.
Defender Hassan Abbas stepped up to intercept a long ball into the penalty area in the 84th minute but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of the Bitar goal.
Nader Jokhadar had given Syria the lead with a well-placed header in the seventh minute.
Japan then laid siege to the Syrian penalty area for most of the match, but rarely managed to break through the Syrian defence.
Bits saved well when they did.
Japan coach Shu Kamo said: ''The Syrian own goal turned out to be a lucky match for us.
The Syrians scored early and then played defensively and used long balls which made it difficult for us.'
Japan, who co-hosted the 2002 World Cup and are ranked 20th in the world by FIFA, are favourites to regain their title here.
Hosts UAE face Kuwait and South Korea face Indonesia on Saturday in Group A.
All four teams are on the same level with one point each from one match.

FOOTBALL - LATE GOALS GIVE JAPAN VICTORY OVER SYRIA.
Two goals in the last six minutes gave Japan an uninspiring 2-1 Asian Cup victory over Syria on Friday.
Takuya Takagi scored the winner in the 88th minute of the Group C match after goalkeeper Salem Bitar spoiled a flawless game by letting the ball slip under his body.
It was the second Syrian defensive breach in four minutes.
Defender Hassan Abbas stepped up to intercept a long ball into the penalty area in the 84th minute but only managed to deflect it into the top corner of the Bitar goal.
Syria had taken the lead after their first serious attack in the seventh minute.
Nader Jokhadar headed a cross from the right from Ammar Awad into the top right corner of Kenichi Shimokawa's goal.
Japan then laid siege to the Syrian penalty area and had a goal disallowed for offside in the 16th minute.
A minute later, Bitar made a good double save, first from Kazuyoshi Miura's header and then blocking Takagi's subsequent shot.
Bitar again saved well from Miura in the 37th minute, parrying away his header from a corner.
Japan started the second half brilliantly but Bitar prevented them from equalising when he dived to his right to save Naoki Soma's low cross in the 53rd minute.

FOOTBALL - THE BAN ON BLINKERS WAS LIFTED.
Dutch striker Reggie Blinker had his indefinite suspension upheld by FIFA on Friday and was due to make a comeback for Sheffield Wednesday against Liverpool on Saturday.
Blinker missed the club's last two matches after FIFA issued a worldwide ban on him for appearing to sign contracts for both Wednesday and Udinese while playing for Feyenoord.
The FIFA Players' Status Committee, meeting in Barcelona, decided that although Udine's document was valid in principle, it could not be legally protected.
The committee considered that the Italian club had broken the rules by not informing Feyenoord, with whom the player had a contract.
Blinker was fined 75,000 Swiss francs ($57,600) for not informing the English club of his previous involvement with Udinese.
FOOTBALL - LEEDS "BOWYER FINED FOR INVOLVEMENT IN BRAWL WITH FAST FOOD.
Leeds England U21 striker Lee Bowyer was fined £4,500 ($7,400) on Friday for throwing chairs at restaurant staff during a brawl at a McDonald's fast food restaurant.
The 19-year-old Bowyer, who was caught on CCTV, pleaded guilty to a charge of affray at a London court.
He was fined and ordered to pay a total of £175 to two employees who were injured in the brawl at an east London restaurant in October.
Leeds had already fined Bowyer £4,000 ($6,600) and warned him that a repeat of his criminal behaviour could cost him his place in the team.
Bowyer, who moved to the Yorkshire club in August for £3.5 million ($5.8 million), was expected to play against Middlesbrough on Saturday.

RUGBY UNION - LITTLE TO MISS CAMPESE FAREWELL.
Centre Jason Little will miss Australia's match against the Barbarians at Twickenham on Saturday.
Little has chosen not to risk aggravating the knee injury that prevented him from playing much of the tour and will be replaced by Queenslander Daniel Herbert.
Owen Finegan has recovered from the knocks he received in last weekend's Test against Wales and retains his place in the backline ahead of Daniel Manu.

The Wallabies are aiming for a 13th consecutive win to end their European tour with a 100 per cent result, but they also want to turn on the style and give David Campese a fitting send-off in his final match in Australian colours.
The Wallabies currently have no plans to give the 34-year-old winger any special presentation, but 75,000 spectators will still gather in the hope of witnessing one last magical moment.
Campese will face a familiar opponent in the form of Barbarians captain Rob Andrew, the man who kicked Australia to defeat with a last-gasp drop-goal in the World Cup quarter-final in Cape Town.
"Campo has a huge following in this country and has had the audience with him ever since he first played here in 1984," says Andrew, who is also likely to make his final appearance at Twickenham.
During the tour, Australia have won all four Tests against Italy, Scotland, Ireland and Wales, scoring 414 points at an average of almost 35 points per match.

The league duties limited the Barbarians' options, but they still have 13 national team players, including England defender Tim Stimpson and recalled winger Tony Underwood, as well as All Black forwards Ian Jones and Norm Hewitt.

FOOTBALL - PLAYERS WHO ARE NOT ELIGIBLE TO PLAY ARE CALLED UP TO FACE MACEDONIA.
Romania coach Anghel Iordanescu on Friday called up three players who have not yet played in his squad to face Macedonia next week in a World Cup qualifier.

Midfielder Valentin Stefan and striker Viorel Ion from Otelul Galati and defender Liviu Ciobotariu from National Bucharest are the newcomers to the European Group Eight clash in Macedonia on 14 December.
Iordanescu said that he had selected them because of their good performance in the domestic championship where National Bucharest is in the top and Otelul Galati in third place. "
I think it's fair to give them a chance," he told reporters.
Team captain Steaua Bucharest, who finished last in their Champions League group in the European Cup, has only two players in the squad.
Offensive midfielder Adrian Ilie, who recently moved from Steaua to Turkish club Galatasaray, is suspended after two yellow cards.

CRICKET - LARA SUFFERS ANOTHER MISERABLE DAY.
Australia gave Brian Lara yet another reason to be unhappy when they beat the West Indies by five wickets in the opening game of the World Series limited overs on Friday.
Lara, who was disciplined on Wednesday for inappropriate behaviour, was awarded five points, extending a disappointing run of form on the tour.
Australia, who have a 2-0 lead in the five-match Test series, outscored the West Indies by 172 runs with eight balls to spare and ended a run of six straight one-day losses.
All-rounder Greg Blewett steered his team to a comfortable victory with an unbeaten 57 in 90 balls, delighting the 42,442 spectators.
Blewett, who was man of the match, entered the court at 70-2 and hit three fours in an untroubled opening 129 minutes.
His crucial fifth match with all-rounder Stuart Law, who scored 21 points, produced 71 points from 85 balls.
Lara looked to be untrained during his brief stay on the pitch before making a simple catch to Shane Warne at mid-wicket.
West Indies tour manager Clive Lloyd has apologised for Lara's behaviour on Tuesday.
He (Lara) had told Australia's coach Geoff Marsh that wicketkeeper Ian Healy was not welcome in the visitors' dressing room.
The Melbourne crowd was clearly upset by the incident and loudly jeered the West Indian vice-captain as he walked to the centre.
It was up to left-hander Shivnarine Chanderpaul to hold the innings together with 54 runs despite having an injured groin.
Chanderpaul was forced to rely on a runner for most of his inning after injuring himself while running back to his seat to avoid being thrown out.
Pakistan, which arrives in Australia later this month, is the second team to take part in the World Series tournament.

CRICKET - LARA SUFFERS MORE MISERY ON AUSTRALIAN TOUR.

West Indies batsman Brian Lara suffered another setback on his Australia tour, having already been disciplined for inappropriate behaviour, when he was dismissed cheaply in the first limited overs match against Australia on Friday.
Lara, who was sternly reprimanded by his own tour management after an angry outburst at Australia wicketkeeper Ian Healy, scored five runs to extend his poor form with the bat.
The West Indies vice-captain struggled for his timing during his 36-minute stay in the crease before hitting a ball from the medium-paced Tom Moody straight to Shane Warne at mid-wicket.
West Indies were 53-2 after 15 overs when rain stopped play at the Melbourne Cricket Ground after captain Courtney Walsh won the toss and elected to bat.
Lara's outburst three days ago has apparently turned some of the Australian public against him.
When he went to the wicket, he was met by loud jeers from parts of the crowd.
On several occasions during his innings, the crowd joined in a series of obscene chants against him.

Tour manager Clive Lloyd apologised on Wednesday for Lara's behaviour when he confronted Australia coach Geoff Marsh in the opponents' dressing room to protest against his suspension in the second test on Tuesday.
Lloyd did not say what the discipline would look like.

Lara, who holds the record for the highest score in Test and first-class cricket, was unhappy with Healy's role in the incident and questioned whether the ball had carried through to the Australian keeper.
Australia went on to win the match at the Sydney Cricket Ground by 124 runs and took a two-nil lead in the five-Test series after Lara failed in both innings.
Lara has yet to make a century since the West Indies arrived in Australia five weeks ago.
Both West Indies and Australia's team management have played down the incident, stressing that relations between the two sides have not been adversely affected.
Pakistan, arriving next week, is the third team in the triangular World Series tournament.
